  "business_context": "Household records anchor family-unit donor management. The pattern emerged because a married couple who give jointly should be acknowledged jointly (\"Dear Mr. and Mrs. Smith\") and have their giving rolled up at the household level for major-donor recognition — but each spouse is still an individual Contact for personalization, communication preferences, and individual interactions. The Household is the bridge. Modeling diverges sharply: NPSP makes Household a Record Type on Account (every Contact gets auto-assigned to a Household Account by default); CiviCRM makes Household a contact_type alongside Individual and Organization (one entity, three subtypes); Bloomerang doesn't have Household as a first-class entity — uses Relationships between individual Constituents to build family connections; the B2B systems (Salesforce vanilla, HubSpot, Attio, EspoCRM) have no native Household concept and require custom build-out for nonprofit deployments. Household giving rollups (the family's lifetime giving across all member donations) are a defining feature of Household models — without them, you can't see \"this family has given $50K over 10 years\" without manual aggregation. When interviewing clients, surface \"Household\" by asking whether they need to track family-unit giving separately from individual giving, whether acknowledgments go to households or individuals, and how they handle joint donations from married couples.",
